===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|pea||peacock}} + {{m|enm|coc}} (see [[cock#Noun|cock (n.)]]). ''Pea'', still used in [[w:Early Modern English|Early Modern English]] but later combined with ''cock'' to deter confusion with the homonymous vegetable, is from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|pēa||peafowl}}, a by-form of {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|pāwa||peafowl}} (whence {{etyl|enm|-}} {{m|enm|po||peacock}}), from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|pavo}} (gen. ''pavonis''), which, with {{etyl|grc|-}} {{m|grc|ταώς}}, said to be ultimately from {{etyl|ta|en}} {{m|ta|தோகை}} (but perhaps is imitative; Latin represented the peacock's sound as ''paupulo''). Used as the type of a vainglorious person from late 14c. Its flesh superstitiously believed to be incorruptible (even St. Augustine credits this). "When he sees his feet, he screams wildly, thinking that they are not in keeping with the rest of his body."

